## When

- Editing existing files or adding small, targeted changes.
- Touching shared modules, public APIs, or behavior-sensitive paths.

## Do

- Read surrounding code and follow local naming, patterns, and import style.
- Keep diffs minimal: one coherent change set that solves the stated problem.
- Prefer one coherent implementation path over leaving parallel experiments in the tree.
- Reuse existing helpers and abstractions instead of duplicating parallel logic.
- Match error-handling, logging, and validation patterns used in the same layer.
- Keep types honest; fix sources of type errors rather than loosening checks broadly.
- Preserve unrelated comments and structure unless removal is required for correctness.

## Don’t

- Drive-by refactors, formatting sweeps, or “cleanup” outside the request.
- Add new dependencies without clear need and alignment with the project.
- Add verbose comments, extra defensive branches, or new docs unless asked.
- Delete or rewrite large unrelated regions to “make it nicer.”
- Turn off strict checks or suppress warnings broadly to avoid fixing root causes.
